==Production==
===Origins===
{{See also|The Blues Brothers}}
The characters, Jake and Elwood Blues, were created by Belushi and Aykroyd in performances on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''. The name "The Blues Brothers" was the idea of [[Howard Shore]]. The fictional back story and character sketches of [[blood brother]]s Jake and Elwood were developed by Aykroyd in collaboration with Ron Gwynne, who is credited as a story consultant for the film.  As related in the liner notes of the band's debut album, ''[[Briefcase Full of Blues]]'', the brothers grew up in an [[orphanage]], learned the blues from a janitor named Curtis and sealed their brotherhood by cutting their middle fingers with a steel string said to have come from the [[guitar]] of [[Elmore James]].<ref name="Bio">{{cite web | title=Fortune City-Blues Brothers | work=Biography of the Blues Brothers-From their album, A Briefcase Full of Blues | url=http://www.fortunecity.com/tinpan/fitzgerald/12/bio.html|accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref>

When it was decided the act could be made into a film by [[Universal Pictures]], Aykroyd set about writing the script. He had never written a [[screenplay]] before, he said in the 1998 documentary, ''Stories Behind the Making of The Blues Brothers'', and he put together a very descriptive volume that explained the characters' origins and how the band members were recruited. It was 324 pages, which was three times longer than a standard screenplay. To soften the impact, Aykroyd made a joke of the thick script and had it bound with the cover of the [[Los Angeles]] [[Yellow Pages]] directory for when he turned it in to producer [[Robert K. Weiss]]. [[John Landis]] was given the task of editing the script into a usable screenplay.<ref name="DVD doc">''Stories Behind the Making of The Blues Brothers'', documentary feature on 1998 DVD and 25th Anniversary DVD (2005).</ref>

The premise of the underlying plot, that a church-owned orphanage would have to pay a property tax bill, has been questioned<U+2014>in Illinois, and generally elsewhere in the world, religious property is exempt from taxes. However, at the time of writing of the film, a legislative proposal to tax such property was under consideration. The proposal was never enacted into law.<ref name="411Mania">{{cite web|title=411Mania | work=Band: The Blues Brothers Movie: The Blues Brothers | url=http://www.411mania.com/music/columns/44932|accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref>

===Location===
Much of the film was shot on location in and around [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]] between July and October 1979.<ref name="BBC">{{cite web | title=Blues Brothers Central | work=The Blues Brothers : About The Movie | url=http://www.bluesbrotherscentral.com/movie1.php?moviepage=about | accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref> Made with the cooperation of [[Mayor of Chicago|Mayor]] [[Jane Byrne|Jane M. Byrne]], it is credited for putting Chicago on the radar as a venue for filmmaking.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://chicago.straightdope.com/sdc20091015.php |title=Were no movies made in Chicago while Richard J. Daley was mayor? |author=Cecil Adams |date=October 15, 2009 |work=Straight Dope Chicago |publisher=Chicago Reader |accessdate=October 30, 2009 }}</ref>  Nearly 200 movies have been [[List of movies set in Chicago|filmed in Chicago]]. "Chicago is one of the stars of the movie.  We wrote it as a tribute," Dan Aykroyd told the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' in an article written to mark the film's 25th anniversary DVD release.<ref name="Chicago Sun-Times">{{cite news|last=Newbart|first=Dave|title=They 'were on a mission from God'|publisher=''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20050825134024/http://www.suntimes.com/output/news/cst-nws-bbintro20.html|date=June 20, 2005|accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref>

[[File:Blues Brothers car chase.JPG|thumb|left|alt=Film screenshot showing a police car driving through a shopping mall. Scattered items are present on the floor and people are running away from the vehicle. Stores visible in the mall include Toys 'R' Us and Jewel.|The Bluesmobile races through the mall while being chased by State Troopers.]]

The first traffic stop was in [[Park Ridge, Illinois]]. The [[shopping mall|mall]] [[car chase]] was filmed in the real, albeit abandoned, [[Dixie Square Mall]] in [[Harvey, Illinois|Harvey]].<ref name="CLUI">{{cite web|title=The CLUI Land Use Database-Dixie Square Mall|work=The Center for Land Use Interpretation|url=http://www.clui.org/clui_4_1/ludb/sites/IL6020.html | accessdate=December 16, 2008|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080120004258/http://www.clui.org/clui_4_1/ludb/sites/IL6020.html |archivedate = January 20, 2008|deadurl=yes}}</ref> The bridge jump was filmed on an actual drawbridge, the 95th Street bridge over the [[Calumet River]], on the southeast side of Chicago. The main entrance to [[Wrigley Field]] (and its sign reading "Save lives. Drive safely, prevent fires.") makes a brief appearance when the "Illinois Nazis" visit it after Elwood falsely registers the ball field's location, 1060 West Addison, as his home address on his driver's license. (Elwood's Illinois driver's license number is an almost-valid encoded number, with Dan Aykroyd's own birth date embedded). The other chase scenes included Lower [[Wacker Drive]], Lake Street and [[Richard J. Daley Center]].<ref name="KF1">{{cite web|title=The Blues Brothers - Chicago Filming Locations|work=Locations in the Blues Brothers|url=http://kevinforsyth.net/film/blues.htm|accessdate=December 16, 2008|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080524050219/http://kevinforsyth.net/film/blues.htm |archivedate = May 24, 2008|deadurl=yes}}</ref>

In the final car chase scene, the production actually dropped a [[Ford Pinto]], representing the one driven by the "Illinois Nazis," from a helicopter at an altitude of more than a mile<U+2014>and had to gain a [[Special Airworthiness Certificate]] from the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] to do it.<ref name="DVDLaser">{{cite web|title=The Blues Brothers|work=DVD Laser|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20071014070914/http://dvdlaser.com/search/detail.cfm?id=22868|accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref> The FAA was concerned that the car could prove too [[aerodynamic]] in a high-altitude drop, and pose a threat to nearby buildings.  The shot leading up to the car drop, where the "Illinois Nazis" drive off a freeway ramp, was shot in [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]] near the [[Hoan Bridge]] on [[Interstate 794]].  The [[Lake Freeway|Lake Freeway (North)]] was a planned but not completed 6-lane freeway and [[Interstate 794|I-794]] contained an unfinished ramp that the Nazis drove off.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wisconsinhighways.org/milwaukee/lake.html|title=Milwaukee Freeways: Lake Freeway|first=Christopher|last=Bessert|accessdate=December 16, 2008|publisher=Wisconsin Highways}}</ref> Several Milwaukee skyscrapers are visible in the background as the [[Bluesmobile]] flips over, notably the [[US Bank Center (Milwaukee)|US Bank Center]].

The "Palace Hotel Ballroom," where the band performs its climactic concert, was at the time of filming a country club, but later became the [[South Shore Cultural Center]], named after the Chicago neighborhood in which it is located. The interior concert scenes were filmed in the [[Hollywood Palladium]].<ref name="EI">{{cite web|title=Chicago-The Blues Brothers|work=Onscreen Illinois|url=http://www.enjoyillinois.com/movies/region-chicago.html|accessdate=December 16, 2008|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080403230610/http://www.enjoyillinois.com/movies/region-chicago.html |archivedate = April 03, 2008|deadurl=yes}}</ref>

The filming in downtown Chicago was conducted on Sundays during the summer of 1979, and much of the downtown was cordoned off from the public. Costs for filming the largest scene in the city's history, totaled $3.5 million.<ref name="HappyRam">{{cite news|last=Newbart|first=Dave|coauthors=Abdon Pallasch|title=Happy to have Bluesmobile ram Daley Center <U+2014> County Building's doors harder to pry open|publisher=''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CSTB&p_theme=cstb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=10B5811C111BC6A8&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|format=Registration required|date=June 24, 2005|accessdate=June 2, 2009}}</ref> Permission was given after Belushi and Aykroyd offered to donate $50,000 to charity after filming.<ref name="HappyRam"/> Although the Bluesmobile was allowed to be driven through the Daley Center lobby, special breakaway panes were temporarily substituted for the normal glass in the building.<ref name="HappyRam"/><ref name="50Greatest">{{cite news|last=Jevens|first=Darel|title=The 50 Greatest Chicago Moments|publisher=''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''|url=http://www.suntimes.com/chicago/best/325489,CST-FTR-film_moments04.article|accessdate=June 2, 2009 | date=April 4, 2007}}</ref> The speeding car caused $7,650 in damages to 35 granite pavers and a bronze air grille in the building.<ref name="HappyRam"/> Interior shots of the elevator, staircase, and assessor's office were all re-created in a filmset for filming.<ref name="HappyRam"/>

===Bluesmobile===
{{Main|Bluesmobile}}
The film used 13 different cars bought at auction from the [[California Highway Patrol]] to depict the [[Bluesmobile]], a retired 1974 [[Mount Prospect, Illinois]] [[Dodge Monaco]] patrol car.  The vehicles were outfitted by the studio to do particular driving chores; some formatted for speed and others for jumps, depending on the scene. For the large car chases, filmmakers purchased 60 police cars at $400 each, and most were destroyed at the completion of the filming.<ref name="Chicago Sun-Times2">{{cite news|last=Newbart|first=Dave|title=Incredible stunt driving: "That was all real"|publisher=''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20050728125722/http://www.suntimes.com/output/news/cst-nws-bbcarchase23.html|date=June 23, 2005|accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref> More than 40 stunt drivers were hired and the crew kept a 24-hour body shop to repair cars.<ref name="Chicago Sun-Times2">{{cite web | title=Chicago Sun-Times | work=Incredible stunt driving: "That was all real" | url=http://web.archive.org/web/20050728125722/http://www.suntimes.com/output/news/cst-nws-bbcarchase23.html | accessdate=December 16, 2006}}</ref>

For the scene when the Blues Brothers finally arrive at the Richard J. Daley Center, a mechanic took several months to rig the car to fall apart.<ref name="Chicago Sun-Times2"/> The statues, seeming to be looking on with concern when the car disassembles, actually exist at the [[Chicago City Hall|Cook County Building]]. At the time of the film's release, it held the world record for the most cars destroyed in one film until it was surpassed by [[Blues Brothers 2000|its own sequel]].<ref name="Chicago Sun-Times2" />

===Casting===
In addition to recognized [[soul music|soul]] and [[rhythm and blues|R&B]] stars [[James Brown]], [[Cab Calloway]], [[Ray Charles]], and [[Aretha Franklin]], the members of [[The Blues Brothers]] band are notable for their musical accomplishments as well. [[Steve Cropper]] and [[Donald Dunn]] are architects of the [[Stax Records]] sound and were half of [[Booker T. & the M.G.'s]] - it is Cropper's guitar heard at the start of the [[Sam and Dave]] song "[[Soul Man (song)|Soul Man]]". Horn players [[Lou Marini]], [[Tom Malone (musician)|Tom Malone]], and [[Alan Rubin]] had all played in [[Blood, Sweat & Tears]] and the ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' band. Drummer [[Willie Hall (drummer)|Willie Hall]] had played in the [[Bar-Kays]] and backed [[Isaac Hayes]]. [[Matt Murphy (blues guitarist)|Matt Murphy]] is a veteran [[blues music|blues]] guitarist. Blues performers were featured in the cast as well, with [[John Lee Hooker]] backed by harmonica player [[Big Walter Horton]] and pianist [[Pinetop Perkins]], playing "Boom Boom" on [[Maxwell Street]].

As the band developed at ''Saturday Night Live'', pianist [[Paul Shaffer]] was part of the act and was cast in the film. However, due to contractual obligations with ''SNL'', he was unable to participate. So actor-musician [[Murphy Dunne]] (whose father, [[George Dunne]], was the Cook County Board President) was hired to take his role.<ref name="DVD doc"/> Shaffer later did appear in ''[[Blues Brothers 2000]]''.

[[Carrie Fisher]], [[Kathleen Freeman]], [[Henry Gibson]], and [[John Candy]] were cast in non-musical supporting roles. The film is also notable for the number of [[cameo appearance]]s by established celebrities and entertainment industry figures, including [[Steve Lawrence]] as a booking agent, [[Frank Oz]] as a corrections officer, [[Twiggy]] as a "chic lady" in a [[Jaguar E-type|Jaguar convertible]] whom Elwood propositions at a gas station, and [[Steven Spielberg]] as the Cook County Assessor's clerk. [[John Landis]] plays a state trooper in the mall chase. [[Paul Reubens]] (pre-[[Pee-wee Herman]]) has a small role as a waiter in the Ch<U+00E9>z Paul. [[Joe Walsh]] has a cameo as the first prisoner to jump up on a table in the final scene, and [[Chaka Khan]] is the soloist in James Brown's choir. The character portrayed by Cab Calloway is named Curtis as an homage to [[Curtis Salgado]], a [[Portland, Oregon]], blues musician who inspired Belushi while he was in Oregon filming ''[[Animal House]]''.<ref name="CS">{{cite web|title=Biography|work=Curtis Salgado|url=http://www.curtissalgado.com/biography.html|accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref>

Over 500 extras were used for the next to the last scene, the blockade on the building at Daley Center, including 200 [[National Guard]]smen, 100 state and city police officers, and 15 [[horse]]s.<ref name="HappyRam"/><ref name="Chicago Sun-Times3">{{cite news|title=Blues Brothers 25th Anniversary|publisher=''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''| url=http://web.archive.org/web/20050721084943/http://www.suntimes.com/special_sections/bluebros/|accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref> Additionally, three [[M4 Sherman|Sherman tanks]], three [[helicopter]]s, and three [[Fire apparatus|fire engines]] were used.<ref name="HappyRam"/> The movie ends with a performance of "Jailhouse Rock" in prison.

==Reception==
===Box office===
''The Blues Brothers'' opened on June 20, 1980 with a release in 594 theaters. It took in $4,858,152, ranking second for that week (after ''[[The Empire Strikes Back]]'') and 10th for the entire year. Over the years, it has retained a following through television and home video. The film in total grossed $57,229,890 domestically and $58,000,000 in foreign box offices for a total of $115,229,890.<ref name="BOM">{{cite web|title=The Blues Brothers|work=Box Office Mojo|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=bluesbrothers.htm|accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref> By genre, it is the ninth-highest grossing musical and the tenth-highest earner among comedy [[road movie]]s. It ranks second, between ''[[Wayne's World (film)|Wayne's World]]'' and ''[[Wayne's World 2]]'' (which, coincidentally, also take place in the greater Chicago metropolitan area, in nearby [[Aurora, Illinois]]), among [[Saturday Night Live#Films|films adapted from ''Saturday Night Live'' sketches]].<ref name="BOM"/> Director Landis claimed that ''The Blues Brothers'' was also the first [[Cinema of the United States|American film]] to gross more money overseas than it did in the United States.<ref name="Chicago Sun-Times"/>

===Critical reception===
The film has an 84% positive rating based on 45&nbsp;reviews from critics at the review aggregator website [[Rotten Tomatoes]].<ref name="RT2">{{cite web|title=The Blues Brothers (1980)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/blues_brothers/|accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref> It won the [[Golden Reel Award]] for Best Sound Editing and Sound Effects,<ref name="Envelope">{{cite news | title=The Envelope | work=Every show, every winner, every nominee-Blues Brothers | url=http://theenvelope.latimes.com/factsheets/awardsdb/env-awards-db-search,0,7169155.htmlstory?searchtype=all&query=The+Blues+Brothers&x=0&y=0|accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref> is number 14th on ''[[Total Film]]'' magazine's "List of the 50 Greatest Comedy Films of All Time"<ref name="CZ">{{cite web| title=Film & Movie Comedy Classics|work=Comedy Zone| url=http://www.comedy-zone.net/tv/films/index.htm|accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref> and is number 69 on [[Bravo (US TV channel)|Bravo's]] "100 Funniest Movies".<ref name="Manroom">{{cite web|title=Bravo's 100 Funniest Movies List is Laughable|work=Manroom Magazine|url=http://www.livemanly.com/?p=132|accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref>

''The Blues Brothers'' has been criticized for its simplistic plot and being overly reliant on [[car chase]]s. Among the reviewers at the time of the film's release who held that opinion was [[Roger Ebert]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''. However, Ebert praised it for its energetic musical numbers and said that the car chases were "incredible".<ref name="RE">{{cite news|last=Ebert|first=Roger|authorlink=Roger Ebert|title=The Blues Brothers|publisher=''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]''|url=http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/19800101/REVIEWS/1010306/1023|accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref> In his review for the ''[[Washington Post]]'', Gary Arnold criticized Landis engorging "the frail plot of ''The Blues Brothers'' with car chases and crack-ups, filmed with such avid, humorless starkness on the streets of Chicago that comic sensations are virtually obliterated".<ref name="Arnold">{{cite news|last=Arnold|first=Gary|authorlink=|title=Oh, Brothers!|publisher=''[[Washington Post]]''|url= | accessdate=}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine's Richard Corliss wrote, "''The Blues Brothers'' is a demolition symphony that works with the cold efficiency of a Moog synthesizer gone sadistic".<ref name="Corliss">{{cite news|last=Corliss|first=Richard|authorlink=|title=A Great Rock-'n'-Roll Caravan|publisher=''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,952710-1,00.html | accessdate=September 15, 2009 | date=July 7, 1980}}</ref>

[[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' criticized the film for shortchanging viewers on more details about Jake and Elwood's affinity for African-American culture. She also took director Landis to task for "distracting editing", mentioning the Soul Food diner scene in which saxophonist [[Lou Marini]]'s head is cut off as he dances on the counter. In the documentary, ''Stories Behind the Making of The Blues Brothers'', Landis acknowledges the criticism, and Marini recalls the dismay he felt at seeing the completed film.<ref name="JM">{{cite news|last=Maslin|first=Janet|authorlink=Janet Maslin|title=The Blues Brothers (1980)|publisher=''[[The New York Times]]''|url=http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C05E6D61638F933A15755C0A966948260 | accessdate=December 16, 2008|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071014070449/http://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9C05E6D61638F933A15755C0A966948260 |archivedate = October 14, 2007|deadurl=yes}} {{Dead link|date=August 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref>

On the 30th anniversary, ''[[L'Osservatore Romano]]'', official newspaper of the Vatican, called the film a "Catholic classic" and recommended viewing.<ref>{{cite news | author=Eric J. Lyman | title=Vatican calls <U+2018>Blues Brothers<U+2019> a <U+2018>Catholic classic<U+2019> | url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/37752137/ns/today-entertainment/ | publisher=msnbc.com | date=June 17, 2010 | accessdate=June 17, 2010}}</ref>

===Cult-film status===
:''See also: [[The Blues Brothers#In popular culture|The Blues Brothers in popular culture]]''
''The Blues Brothers'' has become a staple of late-night cinema, even slowly morphing into an audience participation show in its regular screenings at the [[Valhalla Cinema, Melbourne|Valhalla Cinema]], in [[Melbourne]], Australia.<ref name="The Age">{{cite news|last=Coslovich|first=Gabriella|title=A mission from God nears its end|publisher=''[[The Age]]''|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/02/10/1044725733610.html|accessdate=December 16, 2008 | location=Melbourne}}</ref> John Landis acknowledged the support of the cinema and the fans by a phone call he made to the cinema at the 10th anniversary screening, and later invited regular attendees to make cameo appearances in ''[[Blues Brothers 2000]]''. The fans act as the members of the crowd during the performance of "[[Riders in the Sky: A Cowboy Legend|Ghost Riders in the Sky]]".<ref name="ROTBB">{{cite web|title=The Melbourne Blues Brothers go global!|work=The Return of the Blues Brothers|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20020720111421/blues.squidly.org/ | accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref>

In August 2005, there was a 25th anniversary celebration for ''The Blues Brothers'' at [[Grauman's Chinese Theatre]] in [[Los Angeles]].<ref name="Blues Brothers Central">{{cite web|title=Blues Brothers 25th Anniversary DVD Launch|work=Blues Brothers Central|url=http://www.bluesbrotherscentral.com/movies/the-blues-brothers/anniversary/|accessdate=April 27, 2009}}</ref> Attendees included Landis, former [[Universal Studios]] executive [[Thom Mount]], movie editor [[George Folsey Jr.]], and cast members [[James Brown]], [[Henry Gibson]], [[Charles Napier (actor)|Charles Napier]], [[Steve Cropper]], and [[Stephen Bishop (musician)|Stephen Bishop]].  It featured a press conference, a panel discussion where [[Dan Aykroyd]] joined via satellite, and a screening of the original theatrical version of the film. The panel discussion was broadcast directly to many other cinemas around the country.

==Release==
===Home media===
When the film was first screened for a preview audience, a producer demanded that director John Landis cut 25 minutes from the film.<ref name="Home Theater">{{cite web|last=Chiarella|first=Chris|title=John Landis, Uncensored|work=Home Theater| url=http://www.hometheatermag.com/news/101305landis/|date=October 14, 2005|accessdate=December 16, 2008}}</ref> After trimming 15 minutes, it was released in theaters at 133 minutes. The film's original length was restored to 148 minutes for the "Collector's Edition" [[DVD]] and a Special Edition [[VHS]] release in 1998. The 25th anniversary DVD release in 2005 includes both the theatrical cut and the extended version.

===Soundtrack===
{{Infobox album|
 | Name        = The Blues Brothers: Music from the Soundtrack
